<v Nathaniel>And I, you know, immediately my allergy and reaction to that is to think that, you know, one-track thinking is not one as you might think.</v>

00:46:36.460 --> 00:46:43.920
<v Nathaniel>That every iteration of that serial progression is there – it's going to diverge in really weird ways.</v>

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:54.440
<v John>That the addition of something new, you know, is going to – like, in other words, that, you know, that linearity is not as constraining as it might seem.</v>

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:58.640
<v John>I wonder how Heidegger would sound differently after performativity, you know?</v>

00:46:58.800 --> 00:47:02.860
<v John>Like if he'd had the conceptual framework of performativity – I mean, he didn't.</v>

00:47:02.940 --> 00:47:09.060
<v John>He wasn't alive during, you know, the sort of Austin, Wittgenstein, whatever.</v>

00:47:09.060 --> 00:47:12.640
<v John>But – because he doesn't think – he doesn't quite go.</v>

00:47:13.020 --> 00:47:15.520
<v John>But it does seem like – I mean, I'm with you, Nathaniel.</v>

00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:17.480
<v John>Like everything seems to want to go there.</v>

00:47:17.600 --> 00:47:21.480
