00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:24.500
<v John>There is an action and then residually the big idea of a subject, you know.</v>

00:48:25.140 --> 00:48:45.600
<v Nathaniel>I'll push back on that a bit because I think precisely his concern is the action of calculus preceding the subject because it is constitutive of a particular kind of subjectivity and relatedness to the world, which is why it's not because you're lazy or because, you know, you're doing the wrong things.</v>

00:48:45.600 --> 00:48:56.200
<v Nathaniel>It's because your involvement is essentially with a calculating – within, you know, the performative of calculus.</v>

00:48:56.460 --> 00:48:56.640
<v John>Right.</v>

00:48:56.740 --> 00:48:58.260
<v John>But you're absolutely right.</v>

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:07.680
<v John>So what's being made here is subjects – that's why no one is being lazy is because they're being made by a sort of process that trains him to think in this particular way.</v>

00:49:07.680 --> 00:49:11.780
<v John>But what he can't do is get to the sort of serial differential responses.</v>

00:49:12.440 --> 00:49:16.120
<v John>That's what I mean because it's just like, well, all of that is going to be inauthentic.</v>

00:49:16.600 --> 00:49:20.680
<v John>And even the thing that I held out the hope as being authentic is still going to end up being inauthentic.</v>

00:49:21.320 --> 00:49:34.900
<v John>And it's like that to me is like what is so appealing about the Nietzschean-Deleuzian register is that all you can do in the face with perpetual inauthenticity is say none of it's inauthentic.</v>

00:49:35.440 --> 00:49:35.640
<v John>Right.</v>

00:49:35.720 --> 00:49:44.140
<v John>Like it is just a series of serial differential responses that there's not a question of one being true thinking anymore.</v>

00:49:44.280 --> 00:49:50.460
<v John>I mean we're past that point, I think, historically, conceptually of saying this is real thinking.</v>

00:49:50.900 --> 00:49:51.640
<v John>That's not.</v>

00:49:52.280 --> 00:49:52.580
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:49:52.760 --> 00:49:56.320
<v John>And he can't get there and that's really what I meant.</v>

00:49:56.980 --> 00:49:57.440
<v John>It's weird.</v>

00:49:57.680 --> 00:49:57.940
<v John>Yeah.</v>

00:49:58.340 --> 00:50:05.980
<v John>Everything seems to be straining towards that, but it's also constrained by – and I know I'm using his kind of language, right?</v>

00:50:05.980 --> 00:50:16.920
<v John>But it's constrained by his holding on to the notion of the true and the authentic, even though that true and authentic and those essences are not going to function the way that they previously did.</v>

00:50:17.500 --> 00:50:26.460
