00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:50.860
<v Nate>It's like – and I get that.</v>

00:52:50.940 --> 00:52:54.840
<v Nate>I mean everybody sort of has a vague feeling of that, right?</v>

00:52:54.840 --> 00:53:02.080
<v Nate>I mean with the speed of society, with information technologies, it's like we all feel a little bit like crazy, you know.</v>

00:53:02.080 --> 00:53:05.660
<v Nate>And it would be nice to have a return to a hardness of reality.</v>

00:53:17.160 --> 00:53:31.740
<v Nathaniel>So we made the connection to Marx before and alienated labor and means of production and what's interesting to me is just how, in some ways, post-human Heidegger is in a relationship to Marx.</v>

00:53:31.800 --> 00:53:48.820
<v Nathaniel>Because whereas Marx essentially cares about the laborers and alienation, Heidegger doesn't – for all of his Dasein – I mean like – well, actually, in virtue of his Dasein stuff, he doesn't talk about humans all that much.</v>

00:53:48.820 --> 00:53:49.800
<v Nathaniel>He talks about –</v>

00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:50.100
<v John>No, right. No, you're right.</v>

00:53:50.160 --> 00:54:15.540
<v Nathaniel>Like, I mean it is – from the – the essential term that we're always very too quick to sort of translate as man or human, you know, Dasein, you know, his concern with inauthentic relationships frankly has to do – less to do with like, you know, the exploitation of the human and more about the reduction of the wood to resource.</v>

00:54:15.540 --> 00:54:16.100
<v John>Right.</v>

00:54:16.200 --> 00:54:16.420
<v John>Right.</v>

00:54:16.840 --> 00:54:17.280
<v John>Would.</v>

00:54:17.380 --> 00:54:17.820
<v John>Yeah, that's true.</v>

00:54:17.840 --> 00:54:25.620
<v Nathaniel>What is being violated and it's sort of the shutting down of its capacity to relate to human involvement.</v>

00:54:26.380 --> 00:54:30.580
